Except Weston. He's basically your average beta-male Millennial... in space... on steroids. He has bigger muscles than the Gladiator wannabe, but couldn't fight his way out of a paper bag. And he whines. A lot. The 8 year old girl acts like more of a man than he does. It could honestly be a 4-star movie without his disgraceful character concept.

There's very little CGI, and absolutely appalling physics that make no sense. A good Sci Fi movie about a space ship traveling for more than 40 years in space to try to find a habitable planet. Finally, a beacon is picked up, coming from a worm hole. A scout ship of several of the youngest and best go to investigate, but their scout ship breaks up on entry into the foreign atmosphere. The Captain is injured, and Kate Mitra single-handedly fights off aggressive humanoids as well as ugly bipedal monsters to save her Captain. The ending is uplifting, and the movie is well-worth seeing. Five stars.

Fast-paced, low-budget, clean, sci-fi-channel-level adventure with good acting from the young female lead and Kevin Sorbo. I enjoyed the movie when the young female lead was on the move. But so much of the time the physical confrontations came about in unrealistic ways. Rather than hide, then strike, or hide and avoid, the girl would confront every group of potential adversaries, even when some of them were armed, or she was outnumbered in a major way. These low-budget sci-fi and horror movies repeat the same ridiculous contrivances to get confrontations started or body counts increased. It amazes me that the writers of these low-budget films can't be more creative. This movie was quite clean, however, which was refreshing: no profanity, vulgarity, nudity, sex, or gratuitous violence.

This is sci-fi flick set in a post apocalyptic world where a woman who is survivor of scout of one of 7 main starships that left Earth in search of a new home.  They go through the portal and the woman gets captured, escapes, and eventually makes a friend who informs her that she is on Earth, but she is 400 years removed from her own time.  The two help each and her people eventually return.

(my wife had horses to rent and did tours also)(this is a movie 'not real'... This is a hard sci-fi flick and with a very plausible plot. This is a low budget movie sure, there's no denying that. I watched this because it was amazon prime. I enjoyed the movie but as another reviewer said, it was a lot of the girl on the cover traveling and making dramatic poses etc. It was good, but not amazing.

I did notice one critique about the girl smiling/laughing when she couldn't get on the horse right away - it was her first encounter with that animal beyond videos and I think she was more enjoying learning how to deal with the animal in that moment than anything. If you can't learn to have humor in a bad situation and enjoy the brief moments where you learn and aren't in imminent danger, you will break - she showed humor in her failures and that she wouldn't be the one to break. Once she got it down and got on the horse, she became more serious and buckled down to do the task and travel as needed to get to the other character.

There was one well known actor in the movie, but he was more of a bit part than anything - the girl in the movie was the main character and did very well in the role she was given.

The mythology behind the story is actually pretty good or, as one reviewer put it, moving.  It's unfortunate that the writers, director, producers weren't willing/able to put in the extra effort to polish the storyline to keep the viewer fully engaged.  Suspending your disbelief is one thing, but within the narrative, things should track.  One example that shouldn't spoil anything:  it takes the protagonist several tries to mount a horse for the first time, but once she's on she's suddenly fully competent in keeping her seat and handling the reins.  That kind of inconsistency just pops me right out of the story to a eye-rolling "yeah, right!"  Nonetheless, it's a story worth watching, even as a family, and the underlying themes may spark some good conversation.

I watched this not expecting much but was pleasantly surprised.  I suppose since it is a so called "B" movie and the average star rating wasn't all that great it had me going in with my standards proportionately lowered.  Much of what other critical reviewers say is true; cheesy special effects, almost comically marginal costumes, etc.  Nonetheless I found it to be a pretty decent premise as Sci-Fi goes, and certainly entertaining.  Think of a play that is very moving.  The effects are almost by definition bad, but if it's a good story you enjoy it anyway.  That's how I felt after watching Survivor.  Somewhat paradoxically I found Danielle Chuchran as a stereotypical "slender beauty playing a hardened combat veteran" one of the more convincing portrayals of such a role.  I found myself believing it plausible that she could do all the things she is portrayed doing.  And, yeah, she is hot as hell, so there is that.  If you can let go of the need for high production value I think this is a perfectly enjoyable film if you like action &/or sci-fi.

Part of me was wondering how they were able to take the many people dying so lightly at times but I guess that is something that they were just planning for with all of their training. The same training that led a 21 year old girl to be able to go about 11 Kilometers (roughly 6.8 miles), fight off others, find a horse, learn to ride it and then get another 15km to a wrecked ship. Though it does make me wonder why they wouldn't have more advanced battle/medical gear on hand for each person if they're able to have advanced tech in their arms that can communicate, examine plants, and map their movements and locations.

If you approach this like it were a made-for-tv saturday morning movie for kids, then this is ok...PG-13 for some blood.  Cinematography and music are better than a saturday morning movie but don't look for logic in story elements...Very little spacey special effects, the monster costumes are about what you would see in the 1970s.  Acting was surprisingly good.  The actresses are invariably gorgeous and strong with a little gay/bi implication (hand holding with the main star between a husband and his wife, and the husband calls her first thing in the AM to see her when she wakes while he is in bed with his wife, and the star sits between the husband and wife holding hands with both of them on their big space flight)...Male characters are generally helpless.  Kevin Sorbo's character is ok although his screen time is about 15 minutes, and he gets a broken leg and punctured lung so he doesn't do much.  The director, writer, producers are all mormons (and men), while the star is a woman (and a mormon).  The story includes some LDS references (like implying a save-humanity spaceship ratio of one man + multiple hot chicks), but this is outweighed by the reversal of male/female roles and general lack of originality.  The movie rips off Planet of the Apes, the Time Machine (1960), Mad Max, 2001 Space Odyssey (the bone), BSG (1979 version) and some old Star Trek episodes.  If you have a 9 or 10 year old daughter and want her to see a strong actress protagonist, then you might consider letting her watch this but check out the blood early and near the end.  Violence isn't much compared to zombies.  As for the sexuality, (a) it's only implied, (b) barely noticeable, (c) very brief and (d) all the women sport different hair colors, i.e., not all blonde.

Survivor is a fast passed story about a small group of earth people on a star ship, looking for a new home.  Earth was about to be hit by a solor storm with little or no chance for survival, so 7 great space ships set out throughout the galaxy to find another earth like planet to inhabit and keep the human race alive.  A small group of them crash land on a possible new home planet where they run into a group of humanoids that start attacking them.  They also run into a bipedal creature that is out to kill every one to eat.  Plenty of action in this movie.  Good cast and good direction, and a story line that will keep you entertained.  Well worth the watch.

Not bad for a low budget film. Good acting but poor makeup and graphics. It appeared that most of the film was shot on location so no complaint about poor green screen use. The plot was something along the line of star wars meets hunger games meets Jurassic park which was surprisingly interesting. A strong female lead was a great part throughout the film. Fight scenes weren't the most dramatic and it isn't the most emotional or adrenaline filled film by a long shot. Overall it was a nice spin on the end of the world scenario. Three stars due to lack of connection to a majority of the characters and poor makeup which surprisingly took a lot out of the film once you begin to notice it.

This, beyond any shadow of doubt, was in my top ten list....of Bad Science Fiction Flicks. It rates right down there with Plan 10 from Outer Space, Gog, Them, and Inframan.

After you've seen about ten minutes on the planet, you've had your look at Danielle Chuchran's cute, shapely, wrapped in skin-tight leggings bottom, there isn't anything else to recommend this flick. The plot is bad. Kevin Sorbo is Kevin Sorbo. The monsters didn't quite have the zippers on their costumes showing (ala Invaders from Mars), but that's about it. The holographic FX are dated badly now---and not very good, anyway.

All in all, a true waste of an hour and a half.

The script is obviously thrown together, with dialog taken directly from the George Lucas School of Dialog Writing.

Kevin Sorbo is... well, Kevin Sorbo. Ever since God's Not Dead, the shine has thoroughly worn off Mr. Sorbo's reputation and this flick cements him as a hack that just spews his lines with little to no emotion or skill.

You WILL NOT THRILL to the action sequences (Adam West's Batman was more realistic), you WILL NOT ENJOY the character development (there isn't any), and you WILL NOT CARE about any of the characters (2D cardboard cutouts are more valuable).

The good news is that some studio lost its shirt getting this low-budget mess made -- hopefully they went bankrupt so as to never do anything again.

I have seen pictures by MainstayPro before, and I'm familiar with Danielle Chuchran, so when I saw this movie, I decided to watch it. As a writer myself, I have to say that the plotting really isn't the best.  Some of it is also pretty unbelievable (like falling from the upper atmosphere and deploying a parachute at the last minute, then walking away without a scratch). Moreover, the dialogue made me laugh in a few places where it shouldn't have - like telling the girl with the gaping wound in her abdomen that she was going to die, as if this wasn't already obvious. But, all of that being said, I still found myself entertained.  I like Danielle Chuchran's screen presence.  She's very good in action roles, and manages to be an intimidating warrior while still looking and acting feminine, which not every actress can pull off.  I'm also amazed at how talented she is physically. I could be wrong, but it seems like she does most, if not all, of her own stunts, which includes various kinds of combat, leaping from cliffs, rock climbing, and bareback horse back riding.  She's a big part of why I'm giving the movie three stars.  I also did enjoy seeing Kevin Sorbo, and had to laugh at the name Captain Hunter - I wonder if that was meant to be a nod to the TV series Andromeda, where he played Captain Dylan Hunt.

Get ready for some intense scenes of........rock climbing...rock climbing and more rock climbing...did I mention rock climbing? I swear about half the movie is this girl climbing. We get it..its tough terrain where she climbs A LOT. Stop beating our heads over with it. Ok, done w/ that rant. Well now it is time to get to the meat of the movie. WARNING: It for sure is a low budget film so don't expect much on props, acting, costumes...etc. Just talking about the costumes of the planet natives is enough. The actors for the planet natives look like they came to the job in whatever sports or typical post apocalyptic gear they could find in their own closets. I would let that slide if the masks they wore had any purpose at all. The supposed language barrier would have been enough to keep the mystery. There's no need for masks that have no purpose...unless they're hiding the fact that their extras are horribly disfigured!! oh the poor disfigured extras! D: The other majorly annoying thing was the com. Somehow the main lead was able to use hers throughout the movie, but for some unknown reason only a few others could even use their coms...some for next to no time. Could you give us a reason? Such as if you break that arm it stops functioning...or if you loose to much blood..or SOME PLAUSIBLE REASON besides the fact that only ONE PERSON seems to be able to use it consistently. If it wasn't for the annoying lack of consistency in the story I wouldn't have minded the plot too badly but it feels like they didn't think through the background of things which helps w/ the consistency of a story. I graciously gave it 2 stars (though probably only worth 1 star)...its somewhat entertaining...but has a lot of draw backs. Its not worth owning.

As low budget films go, this one is neither great nor bad.  Danielle Chuchran does a decent job with the lead role and the modest script.

The story setup is pretty simple:  some calamity has befallen Earth and the last human survivors launch out in several spaceships to try to find a habitable world to colonize and survive.  One of these receives a "signal" of some kind and tries to follow it to a new planet only to crash-land and encounter hostile aliens.

Danielle Chuchran plays the lead role among the survivors, and Kevin Sorbo appears in a supporting role as a leader and father-figure.  Churchan has screen presence and decent acting skills, enough to make us care about her character within the constraints of a modest storyline and only basic character development.  There are a fair number of action and combat sequences, and Chuchran handles these well.  The fight choreography won't win any awards, but it is one of the stronger elements of the film and builds enough tension to be uncertain of the outcome at times.  There are some brief funny moments here and there of the cheesy variety to lighten up the mood a bit, and the Utah landscape for the alien planet settings is quite nice to look at.

If you are looking for a way to pass some time, this isn't a bad choice.  It's not a great film, but Chuchran's performance and screen presence keep you engaged along with some credible action sequences.  I would like to see her appear again sometime in something with a stronger script.

It was suggested to me to watch this movie by somebody who liked it.  Being as I generally love sci-fi movies, I got right on it.  I thought it was pretty good, albeit somewhat confusing at first, because of some of the life on the planet dressed similar to one another, and it was hard to tell who was "maybe" enemy, and "true" enemy.  It became clear reasonably fast though.  The action is fairly fast and furious, sneaky and clandestine... it tends to keep your attention to the situation, which is a good thing.  Without spoiling the ending, which you probably begin to suspect about a third of the way through the movie, it was definitely an enjoyable experience, and I'll probably watch it again at some point.  The technology portrayed would be unbelievable to older folks that are not up to date with today's fast growing abilities with "smart" devices, and other technical capabilities of today.  The most unbelievable portion of the movie though, is the premise that the sun strips away the natural planetary protection that earth enjoys, and due to this, causes wormholes to form in many places in space.  (rather ridiculous, in my opinion, because you know that there are quadrillions of planets throughout the universe, and billions of them just in our own Milky Way galaxy, and surely there are planets being destroyed someplace, yet science has yet to detect a wormhole)  Ignoring some of the stuff like that, it's still a fun movie to watch.

The movie was poorly written with a few places that didn't pass any common sense tests.  Some of the supporting actors were not that good, but Danielle Chuchran and Kevin Sorbo made the movie a three star instead of a one.  They did a good job and managed to shine a bit in spite of the poor writing.
It was worth viewing, but don't expect an award winning movie.  If you can get past, or just accept, some of the things that didn't make sense such as their ship exploding in space and Danielle's character somehow falling to the planet (somehow being propelled to the planet long before the ship debris and somehow surviving space, atmospheric entry, and the fall) or Kevin's character being able to fight off several predators at once (whom no one had ever before escaped or survived) with a broken leg, punctured lung and nothing but an old femur bone for a weapon... you get my point.
It reminds me of a lower quality knock off of the movie Will Smith and his son did a few years back with Kevin playing Will's role and Danielle playing his son's.  The big difference was that the Will Smith movie was better written and produced.

No one's going to accuse Survivor of trying to achieve high art, and it doesn't try to be.  Interesting and enjoyable: at that, it succeeds.  Except for the mountain climbing.  There's a whole lot of mountain climbing, and after a while you really do wish Kate would hurry up and get where she's going.  Fortunately, she eventually finds a horse, which somehow obviates the need to climb any more mountains, at least for a little while.  But, don't you worry, they get back to climbing things again soon.  A really big mountain.  Some cliffs and hills and gullies.  And some caves.  Lots of caves.

Still, all in all, it's a fun popcorn movie.  If you go in expecting Interstellar, you're going to be disappointed.  If you go in thinking something more like the movie Stargate, you'll be closer to the mark.  3.5 stars.

Based on the cover pose, you expect a Hunger Gamesesque movie.  Instead, you get a bigger budget version of CW's "The 100," and sadly, isn't even as good.  It is virtually the SAME plot:  Earth has become uninhabitable.  They (whoever "they" may be) send people into space to find a new Earth, end up crash landing back on Earth after "X" amount of years in space to find that the inhabitants left behind have changed into something Primal. Then they get kidnapped by the natives, and as you may guess, the young female Heroine named Kay (played by Danielle Chuchran) has to step-up and take charge of what little crew remain, to ensure their survival.  Why Kay you may ask?, Because the MEN on the mission are ALL so inferior to her and must submit to her blond good looks, tight buns, superior fighting skills and strong will. However, In this big budget version (I mean that as sarcastically as possible because the CW's weekly TV saga has better writing, characters, plot development, sets, special effects... etc., ad nauseam), they add in sub-standard wormhole theory (ROCKS??  In wormholes??  REALLY??), bad CGI, Mad Max costuming, Demon-like monsters (because having the indiginous population trying to kill you after you crash land your ship just isn't enough), and Kevin Sorbo (trumpets sound) - the crews fatherly (elderly, more like) Captain who is also injured and needs to be rescued by Kay.  Oh, and a horse.  Don't forget to add in a horse for good measure.

This Sci-Fi film is most definitely aimed at a younger, female audience. There is no swearing, no sex, no nudity.  Just a good looking, well-built, athletic blond who spends approximately 1/3 of the movie running, jumping, climbing, posing and fighting in black spandex.  The plot was played, the dialogue and characters were under developed and boring.

Also, based on The Hunger Games knockoff cover picture, isn't it a tad coincidental that Danielle Chuchran played Katniss back in 2010 in a short feature hoping to get an audition for the role of Katniss Eberdeen?  Even so, the "star" of the movies is still listed as Kevin Sorbo, because Danielle just isn't a name that draws viewers, yet he is a minor character at best.  He should be listed as a Special Guest Star.  If you are just THAT bored, Danielle is the only thing that is worth watching, otherwise take a pass on thus one.

I'm a SciFi fan.  That's a special requirement for really liking this movie.  There are lots of issues regarding production value and you can spot the low-budget special effects, but SciFi, regardless of how big the budget, requires you to suspend your ideas of reality.  It's thespians doing what they do best; acting like they're really believing what they're doing and saying.  You really believe these people if you can suspend disbelief.  Sure, there are some silly parts that don't make sense like the natives speaking English AND some silly Klingon whatever, but so what?  It could happen.  Sure, you wonder why they misplaced their navigation charts and don't realize where they are until halfway through the movie.  It could happen.  Still, it's a fun movie. I get the feeling they're all really enjoying making this movie for us and I enjoyed watching it.  Can't wait for part 2: The Wrath of Khan's survivor.  LOL.

A very quick reply to the comments below about the ' holes ' in the story plot.  First, it's a movie, it's SciFi, and that is common.  Is there any ' scientific ' explaination for the elements of Star Trek stories such as ' warp drive ', ' set phasers to stun ' or ' the Vulcan Mind Meld "? There isn't.

This movie does have some science behind the science fiction. Three quick examples:

1. The Heroine has to climb some forbidding rock formation to gain high ground for radio communcations with her commander and comrades. This is factual. Radio towers are placed on high ground or atop high builldings.
2. There is a relativistic time element. One year on the ' mother ship ' is equal to 10 years on the planets surface due to the temporal effects of the relativistic near-light speed of the mother ship.  This is factual.
3. The scout ship disintegrates in flight leaving a debris field which covers a very large area.  This is an important plot point and anyone who studies aircraft disasters can attest to the factual basis here.

This particular 'SciFi ' movie actually has a good scientific basis for the story.  That's not needed for a good story, but in this case the comments below aren't correct. These aren't ' holes ' in the story, they are scientifically based story elements.

After looking at reviews for this film I was not expecting much going in. most people seemed to dislike this movie and downplayed it. I think that may have actually helped out a bit when I went into this. I was going to get it regardless because Kevin Sorbo was in it. So when I did pick it up I headed over to my brothers house with a few friends for our little all night movie marathons [only when we all have off the next day]. This was the second or third on the list that night and by the end of it there was a mixed reaction in the room.

Kate Mitra [Danielle Chuchran] is one of the last people alive in the universe. She is a solider under Captain Hunter [Kevin Sorbo] who leads this group looking for a planet that could house them. After coming upon a distress signal they make their way for its origins to find such a planet waiting for them. Things don't go as planned as they crash land on the planet to find monsters and murderous humans hunting them down.

Now like I said the room was mixed and split on how we felt about it, some of us enjoyed [me included] while the rest didnt. Now since I read all these bad reviews I had low expectations and I think it helped. I liked how the story played out and how it ended. The action was good and I liked the whole cliffhanger like scenes that some seemed to hate. Sure it was to show off its star but why not. Danielle is a pretty girl and could pull off everything the role required. I thought she did a great job here.

Also I have to point out the whole reason I bought the flick, Kevin Sorbo. As always he was great and played his part very well. In fact I thought everyone in the film did a good job, including writer/director John Lyde. I have enjoyed some other films of his including the other Kevin Sorbo flick One Shot and the zombie film Ozombie. All you get as far as special features is the trailer, like One Shot I wish there was a commentary. Also I want to point out that the creatures on here looked cool, I liked them.

Kind of a cross between The Time Machine, Planet of the Apes and Earth II, this action film highlights a female heroine who fights against all odds to survive on a planet that is actually Earth in the future (a mystery that a 5 year old could guess after the first 15 minutes). A few good CGI effects and an equal number of funky humans made up to look like monsters are upstaged by this super girl who never seems to tire, need to drink or eat and has not the least amount of fear of anything. A mindless piece of fluff to fill an hour or so when you don't have anything better to do (oh, and Kevin Sorbo gives a very boring performance coming off a recent film where he proved that all atheists are poo-poo heads - I half expected him to try and convert us at some point). Yeah, this is a movie not as bad as I thought it would be, but not as good as it could have been if it had a different script, plot, actors and a modicum of originality.

This is a space evacuation story (earth going belly up, 7 ships are sent out with worlds only hope for the future) following one of the lost ships.  The story picks up after 40 years in space, a new generation of 20 somethings in training under the direction of the captian, resident old guy (Kevin Sorbo).  Three main trainees occupy the smart mouth overconfident jock, whiney coward, and shapely heroine slots in the cast.  A signal coming from the nearby discovered wormhole causes the captain and a landing party to send a patrol to investigate the signal, and seconds after entering the wormhole, exit into an asteroid field where the ship is destroyed.  Somehow, you can fall from an asteroid belt into the Earth Atmosphere, and land safely in the ocean.  From there, the story twists and morlock equivalents are hunting the survivors, as are some gas mask tribes of resident humans.  Most of the story is about the feisty heroine (it's a rock climber movie really) getting to the captain, who is holed up in a cave with a broken leg.
Along the way she beats some of the morlocks, finds a horse (space horses are so rare), and befriends one of the tribesman after she attacks him while he is trying to save her form the morlock.  The story turns into a fast ending at that point, and they discover something shocking, and everyone has a happy ending when the mother ship shows up to rescue the crash victims.

I really enjoyed this movie. Five stars for me. Not because it was anchored by Academy Award Winners or it was directed by some legendary figure. No, I enjoyed it because it did what it set out to do on a budget that would make other productions laugh. This movie kept me entertained from beginning to end. That is a rarity, no matter the budget. The acting was very good. The story wasn't something we haven't seen before, but these days what story is? The location was outstanding. Great visuals. Shot in Utah and it shows. I don't know exactly where they shot it, but the smooth rocks, bizarre rock formations and the overall area made for an excellent location for this shoot. Will there be a lot of people out there to agree with me on this? Who knows, I suspect not. I am very generous when I review. If I am entertained and I try to think of negatives and they don't come to mind then why would I give it anything but full marks? Kevin Sorbo is one of those B-genre, fantasy genre guys that I have enjoyed over the years. His work has always entertained me, so he is a winner in my book. Danielle Chuchran is the real lead in this movie and she does an outstanding job. She is pretty bad azz in this. She is in amazing shape. A lot of physical work for her. A lot of running, jumping, fighting with weapons and more. The creatures on this planet were well done by the effects department. Bravo on that one. Great effects both on the ground and in the air. Overall I can't see myself coming up with any complaints.

This is well acted very good action sci fi. A space ship crashes onto an unknown planet, carrying humanities last chance for survival. Or is it? The crew has been training aboard ship all of their lives for combat, and are well prepared for hostility. They find competing forces, mask wearing humanoid warriors, and monster life forms. Ultimate survival will depend on forming an alliance. There are a few surprises to come, well worth the look.

The characters are hollow.  The script is abysmal.  Most of the actors seem like vapid, empty, dim ex-Laker girl rejects or boy band hopefuls.  Truly, I feel sorry for the poor souls who were convinced to invest in this movie.  Next time, put your money in some penny stocks or a cubic zirconia mine... you would have a better chance on a return.
The aliens were laughable (I really have seen better ones on old Flash Gordon videos), the props were childish, and the special effects really put the 'special' in special effects.  Kevin Sorbo's works as a biker and barbarian are like watching Sir John Gielgud compared to this drivel.
I really hate to be so, seemingly, mean about this review, but please, if you were involved in this film, really, for your own sakes, consider a move to a different career path.  There still is time to make something meaningful of your life.  None of you belongs in film (this abortion is to film what Saddam Hussein's boys were to philanthropy and human rights causes).  I hate to say this to, what probably, are very nice people.  However, don't waste your lives anymore.  Regret is a terrible thing.

I was very surprised that this movie was interesting.  I like the actor Kevin Sorbo so I decided to watch it.  It started off a little slow but as the adventure of the "Survivor" named Kate  (actress Danielle Chuchran) started her journey on the planet after her spaceship crashed, it became an intriguing, suspenseful experience of her survival against the planet's aliens. Kate is quite smart and athletic.  I would recommend this movie to any age group.

I'm a fan of low budget films, the skill of the actors rarely annoys me & same with the CGI, Costumes, Make Up, etc. For me it is all about the story, and how it holds up throughout the movie.

Right from the start there were too many holes & inconsistencies, and this persisted all the way to the end of the move. When Kate lands on the planet, some how she lands a good 10 - 20 minutes before everyone else and the ship she was in lands. This created one of the first "action" scenes as there was falling wreckage around her as she ran.

Never mind she falls in water and somehow knows how to swim even though she's been on a ship her entire life. I can get over this, but then she is able to go and save a girl from drowning as well, this is incredibly difficult even for an experienced swimmer.

Then it turns out that Kate has a full computer and body scanner in her arm that lets you know your vitals, etc. Everyone on the ship has this computer, yet Kate is the only one that uses it to find out what's wrong with their bodies? Why can't anyone else scan themselves? (Oh, and we know it's possible to scan oneself because Kate does this as well).

In several of the fighting scenes one alien is almost too much for Kate to handle, and then later on (after she is more tired & hurt) she is able to take on 6 - 8 at a time.

One of the groups of aliens wears a type of "End of the world" gas mask. First initial thought "oh, that alien form can't breath on the surface, okay that makes sense" Nope, they're just wearing these masks that block their line of vision and make them worse off, just because they can.

These are just a few of the many holes & inconsistencies in this movie. It's hard to follow the story and stay attentive to the whole thing because of this.

I guess what got me grinning the most was halfway thru when the girl saves the horse and in no time at all she riding across the badlands like a little cowgirl.  Oh, by the way we happen to  be on a hostile savage planet with a mix of Mad Max characters and rejects from the really really bad monster make up department.  Keep grinning, before you know it, the girl happens upon a campfire where behold! a bridle and bit happen to be lying around. Definitely low budget but at least some time was spent on decent creature makeup and fair cg effects.  Unfortunately, there were instances of cheesy makeup that caught my eye, and the acting, while not bad, did seem forced coming from some of the characters.  Inconsistencies might not bother most people, but annoyed me.  For example, main character travels 40 km, partially on horseback, to come to the aid of her injured captain.  Shortly after, she's right back to where she was when she started (creature lair).  I wish that film makers in general would take small and simple steps toward realism. Characters should actually be dripping wet when just coming out of the water instead of lightly damp.  Mascara shouldn't stay on for a whole movie (should it even exist in this place and time?) and the main character is attractive enough without it.  Minor nitpicks of mine. I fast-forwarded through a lot of parts and don't feel I missed anything.  I probably shouldn't have bothered, but I started it to kill some time and accomplished at least that.

For aficionados of cheap SciFi movies you'd expect more exposed female flesh or, at least,  explicit lycra-adhering views. Though I hoped for such displays of pulchritude, none appeared, but I was not disappointed, the movie was okay.

The film centers on Kay (Danielle Chuchran) which is not short for Katniss, but should be judging by the cover pose. The earth became uninhabitable for kittens so seven ships left through  wormholes to seek out other planets. Kay gives us a monologue to catch us help, spouting bad science to weave a tale. She stays in shape in a simulator where they learn to shoot and play war games. They quickly crash land on a planet which is inhabited by unfriendly aliens who speak a German version of sand creature and wear a Heinz 57 combinations of Mad Max respirators. There are also unfriendly aliens who look like they came from a 1950's film. K manages to save most of the crew by herself, except Anne (Abigail Mason) who was prettier.

Kay has a number of skills apparently acquired in the simulator not shown such as the bow, axe throwing, horse riding, and rock climbing.

The film is a Sci-Fi film aimed at a younger audience. There is no swearing, no sex, no nudity...heck no one even talks about a shower. The dialogue was boring. The characters were boring.

Danielle Chuchran played Katniss back in 2010 in a short feature hoping to get an audition for the role. The Utah company that made this film is also the same one that made Orc Wars/Dragonfyre which accounts for the lack of a quality script. 2 stars for most adults, although I am sure some kids and fans of Danielle Chuchran will enjoy the feature.

I can think of a dozen similar movies, with all but one being worse. $9.96 US Walmart.

This is simply not 5 star entertainment. There are just too many improbabilities... you know things that just would not happen, Like falling 10's of thousands of feet, and popping a too-small-chute at 100 feet and living to tell about it. But, if you are willing to suspend disbelief, the movie is watchable and though there are no Oscar performances here, the acting is good. If you want to spend a couple of hours picking this movie apart, there is lots to find here, but as budget sci-fi goes, there are a lot worse out there. If you are a sci-fi fan, there is a good chance you will enjoy this movie.
This is a pretty good medium budget sci-fi. There are a couple of totally cardboard characters but there's a believable fairly tight plot with decent action. It's entertaining.

I would give it an extra half star, but I wasn't willing to round up. I gauged this movie by how much of it I skipped to get to some interesting part. My ratio was about sixty percent of the movie was "walkabout" in some pretty scenery, but I don't need it in a movie.

I even skipped ahead in most of the action parts. I knew who was going to win in any battle involving Kate. I didn't need any buildup of tension. After watching the first two action scenes, I realized that it wasn't worth the time. It was a predictable storyline that would only have worked with pretty people as heroes and ugly people as bad guys. Good thing they had both in abundance.

Interesting story, worthy of about 25 minutes of film. Look at it this way. You've always wanted to be a Hollywood editor. Now's your chance to leave most of this film on the cutting-room floor.

Enjoy the rest.
